Should I use Unbound (recursive) or dnscrypt-proxy (encrypted forwarding) for maximum privacy?

Executive summary

For maximum privacy, running Unbound as a local, validating recursive resolver is generally the stronger choice because it minimizes trust placed in third‑party DNS providers and validates answers with DNSSEC, keeping most metadata on your network rather than with an external resolver [1][2]. Encrypted forwarding with dnscrypt-proxy gives confidentiality on the wire to a chosen provider and useful anonymity/rotation features, but it shifts trust to that provider and therefore can be worse for end-to-end privacy if you care about exposure to external parties [3][4].

1) Trust model and privacy tradeoffs

The core privacy difference is who you trust: Unbound performs recursive resolution locally and therefore avoids sending all queries to a third‑party operator, meaning you don't have to trust an external resolver's logging and retention policies [1][4]. By contrast, dnscrypt‑proxy encrypts DNS transport to external DoH/DoT/DNSCrypt providers—protecting queries from ISP eavesdropping on the wire—but requires trusting those chosen providers and any relays you enable [3][4].

