2) Encryption and attack surface

If your adversary is a local network or ISP eavesdropper, dnscrypt‑proxy's encrypted forwarding (DoH/DoT/DNSCrypt) prevents passive interception between your network and the provider, which Unbound running over plain UDP/53 will not by default [2][3]. Unbound can be configured to use DoT/DoH for upstreams, however, and supports TLS-based transports when you choose to forward, so encryption is possible with Unbound too — but once you forward you again place trust in that upstream provider [2][4].

3) Integrity and DNSSEC

Unbound emphasizes validation and integrity: running your own recursive resolver lets you validate DNSSEC signatures and obtain answers directly from authoritative servers, reducing risk of tampered responses and making returned IPs more trustworthy [2][1]. Using dnscrypt‑proxy to forward to a DNSSEC-aware provider can still get validated records, but that validation occurs at the provider rather than under your direct control [3][4].

4) Practical performance and reliability

Users report Unbound is lightweight and performant even on low‑end hardware (Pi devices) because it caches results and queries root servers directly, giving fast, fresh responses without relying on external provider availability [5][1]. dnscrypt-proxy can be fast and stable depending on chosen providers and offers extras like provider rotation and anonymized relays, but performance becomes provider‑dependent and you add another network hop [2][6].

5) Common complaints from real users

Common community feedback is that encrypting DNS alone is not a panacea — it doesn't hide destination servers from your ISP if other traffic is unencrypted, and it introduces an additional party you must trust if you forward [5][3]. Users also describe combining tools (Unbound + dnscrypt‑proxy or Unbound + stubby) to get both local validation and encrypted upstreams as a pragmatic compromise, though chaining increases complexity [7][8].

6) Best for — recommendations by use case

If your priority is minimizing external trust and maximizing control and integrity (e.g., privacy‑conscious home lab, Pi‑hole users), choose Unbound as a recursive, DNSSEC‑validating resolver and run it locally [4][1]. If your main threat is an on‑path ISP or local network attacker and you want simple confidentiality with anonymity features (rotation, relays), dnscrypt-proxy pointed at vetted, no‑log providers is a practical choice [3][6]. For most privacy-focused users the optimal setup is hybrid: Unbound locally for recursion and DNSSEC, configured to use encrypted upstreams or dnscrypt-proxy for anything you specifically want hidden or anonymized [6][4].

Bottom line

Run Unbound as your primary resolver for maximum privacy and integrity because it minimizes external trust and performs DNSSEC validation locally; add dnscrypt-proxy or configure Unbound to use DoH/DoT only when you have a clear need to hide queries from your ISP or when you want the anonymity/rotation features of specific providers, but be conscious you then trade some of Unbound's trust advantage for encrypted forwarding [1][3][4]. In short: prefer Unbound local recursion first, use dnscrypt-proxy selectively for encryption/anonymity.